spec: mp3211
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(multiprocessing)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html"
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.managers.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 661 (mp3211): __and__, __or__, __xor__ dict-presence for multiprocessing types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: multiprocessing.Process, pool.Pool, pool.AsyncResult, pool.MapResult, managers.SyncManager, managers.BaseListProxy, managers._BaseDictProxy, managers._BaseSetProxy."
    - "Key finding (__and__): all 8 multiprocessing classes return false for __and__. multiprocessing.Process manages a subprocess lifecycle (start/join/terminate/kill); & is undefined for process objects. pool.Pool dispatches work to worker processes via apply()/map()/starmap(); no bitwise AND is defined. pool.AsyncResult and pool.MapResult are result handles; & is not defined for combining results. managers.BaseListProxy proxies list — list does not define __and__. managers._BaseDictProxy proxies dict — dict does not define __and__. Critical note on managers._BaseSetProxy: this proxy wraps Python's set, which DOES define __and__ (set intersection). However, _BaseSetProxy does NOT store __and__ in its own __dict__ — it accesses set methods via the _method callthrough IPC mechanism. Therefore operator.contains(_BaseSetProxy.__dict__, '__and__') = False even though set intersection is ultimately reachable through the proxy."
    - "Key finding (__or__): all 8 multiprocessing classes return false for __or__. Python's set defines __or__ for set union (s | t), but managers._BaseSetProxy does NOT have __or__ in its own __dict__ — set union operations are proxied via the _method IPC callthrough, not via a locally defined __or__ dunder. multiprocessing.Process/Pool/AsyncResult/MapResult/SyncManager are process-management and result-handle types with no set-algebra semantics. managers.BaseListProxy and managers._BaseDictProxy proxy list and dict respectively; neither list nor dict defines __or__ for bitwise/union purposes (dict.__or__ was added in Python 3.9 for dict merging, but _BaseDictProxy does not expose it in its own __dict__ either)."
    - "Key finding (__xor__): all 8 multiprocessing classes return false for __xor__. Python's set defines __xor__ for symmetric difference (s ^ t), but managers._BaseSetProxy does NOT have __xor__ in its own __dict__ — as with __and__ and __or__, the proxy relies on the _method IPC callthrough mechanism rather than defining operator dunders locally. All remaining types (Process, Pool, AsyncResult, MapResult, SyncManager, BaseListProxy, _BaseDictProxy) have no set-algebra or bitwise data model of any kind."
    - "Critical insight for _BaseSetProxy: Python's set defines __and__/__or__/__xor__ for set intersection, union, and symmetric difference. _BaseSetProxy is a manager proxy for set objects hosted in a manager server process. Despite proxying a type that has these dunders, _BaseSetProxy accesses proxied methods via a _method dispatch mechanism over IPC — it does not define __and__, __or__, or __xor__ in its own __dict__. The expected value is False for all three operators even though set algebra is ultimately reachable through the proxy."
    - "All 24 values in this wave are false. multiprocessing is a process-based concurrency library; its entire API is expressed through explicit method calls, subprocess lifecycle management, and IPC — never through Python's arithmetic or bitwise data model."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __and__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__and__')
#
# All 8 multiprocessing classes return false for __and__.
# Process/Pool/AsyncResult/MapResult: process-management and result-handle
#   types; bitwise AND is not defined for any of them.
# managers.BaseListProxy: proxies list — list does not define __and__.
# managers._BaseDictProxy: proxies dict — dict does not define __and__.
# managers._BaseSetProxy: proxies set — set DOES define __and__ (intersection),
#   but _BaseSetProxy does NOT have __and__ in its own __dict__. The proxy
#   accesses set methods via the _method IPC callthrough mechanism, not via
#   locally defined operator dunders. Result: false.
# managers.SyncManager: server process that hosts shared objects; no
#   bitwise protocol defined in its own __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

