# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __and__, __or__, __xor__ across all 8 multiprocessing subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 8 classes x 3 methods = 24 rows.
# __and__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __or__:  false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __xor__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# All 24 values are false.
# The _BaseSetProxy case warrants special attention:
#   Python's set defines __and__ (intersection), __or__ (union), and
#   __xor__ (symmetric difference) as first-class operator dunders.
#   _BaseSetProxy is a manager proxy wrapping a set object hosted in
#   a separate server process. Despite this, _BaseSetProxy does NOT
#   copy or redefine these dunders in its own __dict__. The proxy
#   dispatches all method calls to the manager server via IPC using
#   the _method callthrough mechanism. Operator dunders are NOT part
#   of the proxied interface — they must be called explicitly as named
#   methods (e.g., proxy.__and__(other)) if exposed, but the dunder
#   is not present in _BaseSetProxy.__dict__ itself.
# _BaseDictProxy note: dict.__or__ was added in Python 3.9 (PEP 584)
#   for the d1 | d2 dict-merge operator. _BaseDictProxy does not expose
#   this in its own __dict__ — the proxy interface does not include
#   dict's __or__ as a locally defined dunder.
# multiprocessing.pool.AsyncResult note: the "Async" prefix refers to
#   non-blocking result retrieval via get(), not to asyncio coroutines.
#   AsyncResult defines no arithmetic or bitwise dunders.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

